\hypertarget{part-1-manipulator-dynamics-1}{%
\subsection{📖 Part 1 --- Manipulator Dynamics}\label{part-1-manipulator-dynamics-1}}

\hypertarget{why-dynamics-matter}{%
\subsubsection{1.1 Why Dynamics Matter}\label{why-dynamics-matter}}

Kinematics tells us \emph{where} the robot moves; dynamics tells us \emph{what forces and torques} are required to produce that motion. Without a dynamic model we cannot design controllers that truly cancel the nonlinear effects of inertia, coupling, Coriolis forces, and gravity.

\hypertarget{feedback-control}{%
\paragraph{🔄 Feedback Control}\label{feedback-control}}

Uses sensor measurements (encoders, IMUs) to adjust torques in real time. Robust against model errors but reacts \emph{after} errors occur.

\hypertarget{feedforward-control}{%
\paragraph{➡️ Feedforward Control}\label{feedforward-control}}

Applies precomputed torques from the dynamic model \emph{before} the error appears. Requires an accurate model but gives faster response.

\hypertarget{combined-computed-torque}{%
\paragraph{⚙️ Combined (Computed Torque)}\label{combined-computed-torque}}

Feedforward cancels known dynamics; feedback corrects remaining error. This is the gold standard for manipulator control.

\hypertarget{the-eulerlagrange-equation-of-motion}{%
\subsubsection{1.2 The Euler--Lagrange Equation of Motion}\label{the-eulerlagrange-equation-of-motion}}

For an \textbackslash(n\textbackslash)-DOF rigid-body manipulator, the Lagrangian \textbackslash(\textbackslash mathcal\{L\} = T - V\textbackslash) (kinetic minus potential energy) yields the standard form:

\textbackslash{[} M(q)\textbackslash,\textbackslash ddot\{q\} \textbackslash;+\textbackslash; C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\} \textbackslash;+\textbackslash; G(q) \textbackslash;=\textbackslash; \textbackslash tau \textbackslash{]}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Symbol & Name & Dimension & Physical Meaning \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\textbackslash(q\textbackslash) & Joint positions & \textbackslash(n \textbackslash times 1\textbackslash) & Generalised coordinates (angles for revolute joints) \\
\textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash) & Mass (inertia) matrix & \textbackslash(n \textbackslash times n\textbackslash) & Relates joint accelerations to required torques; symmetric positive-definite \\
\textbackslash(C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash) & Coriolis \& centrifugal matrix & \textbackslash(n \textbackslash times n\textbackslash) & Velocity-dependent coupling forces between joints \\
\textbackslash(G(q)\textbackslash) & Gravity vector & \textbackslash(n \textbackslash times 1\textbackslash) & Torques required to hold the arm against gravity \\
\textbackslash(\textbackslash tau\textbackslash) & Joint torques & \textbackslash(n \textbackslash times 1\textbackslash) & Control inputs (what we design) \\
\end{longtable}

\hypertarget{a-concrete-example-2-dof-planar-manipulator}{%
\subsubsection{1.3 A Concrete Example: 2-DOF Planar Manipulator}\label{a-concrete-example-2-dof-planar-manipulator}}

Consider a two-link planar arm with link masses \textbackslash(m\_1, m\_2\textbackslash), link lengths \textbackslash(l\_1, l\_2\textbackslash), and distances to centres of mass \textbackslash(l\_\{c1\}, l\_\{c2\}\textbackslash). For simplicity we take \textbackslash(l\_\{ci\} = l\_i\textbackslash) (point masses at link tips).

\hypertarget{mass-matrix-mq}{%
\paragraph{📐 Mass Matrix \textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash)}\label{mass-matrix-mq}}

\textbackslash{[}
M(q) = \textbackslash begin\{bmatrix\}
m\_1 l\_1\^{}2 + m\_2(l\_1\^{}2 + l\_2\^{}2 + 2l\_1 l\_2 \textbackslash cos q\_2) \& m\_2(l\_2\^{}2 + l\_1 l\_2 \textbackslash cos q\_2) \textbackslash\textbackslash{}
m\_2(l\_2\^{}2 + l\_1 l\_2 \textbackslash cos q\_2) \& m\_2 l\_2\^{}2
\textbackslash end\{bmatrix\}
\textbackslash{]}

Notice: \textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash) depends on \textbackslash(q\_2\textbackslash) only (the relative angle), and is always symmetric positive-definite so it is invertible.

\hypertarget{coriolis-centrifugal-matrix-cqdotq}{%
\paragraph{🌀 Coriolis \& Centrifugal Matrix \textbackslash(C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash)}\label{coriolis-centrifugal-matrix-cqdotq}}

Using Christoffel symbols of the first kind:

\textbackslash{[}
C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\}) = \textbackslash begin\{bmatrix\}
-m\_2 l\_1 l\_2 \textbackslash sin(q\_2)\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\}\_2 \& -m\_2 l\_1 l\_2 \textbackslash sin(q\_2)(\textbackslash dot\{q\}\_1 + \textbackslash dot\{q\}\_2) \textbackslash\textbackslash{}
m\_2 l\_1 l\_2 \textbackslash sin(q\_2)\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\}\_1 \& 0
\textbackslash end\{bmatrix\}
\textbackslash{]}

\hypertarget{gravity-vector-gq}{%
\paragraph{⬇️ Gravity Vector \textbackslash(G(q)\textbackslash)}\label{gravity-vector-gq}}

\textbackslash{[}
G(q) = \textbackslash begin\{bmatrix\}
(m\_1 + m\_2)\textbackslash,g\textbackslash,l\_1 \textbackslash cos q\_1 + m\_2\textbackslash,g\textbackslash,l\_2 \textbackslash cos(q\_1 + q\_2) \textbackslash\textbackslash{}
m\_2\textbackslash,g\textbackslash,l\_2 \textbackslash cos(q\_1 + q\_2)
\textbackslash end\{bmatrix\}
\textbackslash{]}

\hypertarget{key-properties-of-the-dynamic-model}{%
\subsubsection{1.4 Key Properties of the Dynamic Model}\label{key-properties-of-the-dynamic-model}}

\hypertarget{property-1-symmetry-positive-definiteness}{%
\paragraph{✅ Property 1: Symmetry \& Positive-Definiteness}\label{property-1-symmetry-positive-definiteness}}

\textbackslash(M(q) = M(q)\^{}T \textgreater{} 0\textbackslash) for all \textbackslash(q\textbackslash). This guarantees the system always has finite inertia and the dynamics are well-posed.

\hypertarget{property-2-skew-symmetry}{%
\paragraph{✅ Property 2: Skew-Symmetry}\label{property-2-skew-symmetry}}

The matrix \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{M\}(q) - 2C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash) is skew-symmetric, i.e., \textbackslash(x\^{}T{[}\textbackslash dot\{M\} - 2C{]}x = 0\textbackslash) for all \textbackslash(x\textbackslash). This property is \textbf{essential} for Lyapunov-based stability proofs.

\hypertarget{property-3-linearity-in-parameters}{%
\paragraph{✅ Property 3: Linearity in Parameters}\label{property-3-linearity-in-parameters}}

The dynamics can be written as \textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash ddot\{q\} + C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash dot\{q\} + G(q) = Y(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\},\textbackslash ddot\{q\})\textbackslash,\textbackslash theta\textbackslash) where \textbackslash(\textbackslash theta\textbackslash) contains the physical parameters. This enables adaptive control.

\hypertarget{thinkpairshare-5-min}{%
\paragraph{Think--Pair--Share (5 min)}\label{thinkpairshare-5-min}}

\textbf{Question:} If the second link mass \textbackslash(m\_2\textbackslash) doubles (e.g., the robot picks up a heavy payload), which terms in \textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash), \textbackslash(C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash), and \textbackslash(G(q)\textbackslash) are affected? Which are \emph{not} affected?

Discuss with your neighbour for 2 minutes, then we will share answers as a class.

\hypertarget{part-2-control-design-for-the-manipulator}{%
\subsection{🎛️ Part 2 --- Control Design for the Manipulator}\label{part-2-control-design-for-the-manipulator}}

\hypertarget{approach-1-simple-pd-control}{%
\subsubsection{2.1 Approach 1: Simple PD Control}\label{approach-1-simple-pd-control}}

The simplest approach is a joint-space PD controller:

\textbackslash{[} \textbackslash tau = K\_P\textbackslash,e + K\_D\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} \textbackslash{]}

where \textbackslash(e = q\_d - q\textbackslash) is the tracking error and \textbackslash(K\_P, K\_D \textbackslash succ 0\textbackslash) are diagonal gain matrices.

This treats the manipulator as if it were a collection of independent linear joints. It ignores nonlinear coupling, Coriolis forces, and gravity entirely.

\textbf{Limitation:} PD control alone cannot guarantee zero steady-state error in the presence of gravity. The arm will droop under its own weight because no term compensates for \textbackslash(G(q)\textbackslash).

\hypertarget{approach-2-pd-gravity-compensation}{%
\subsubsection{2.2 Approach 2: PD + Gravity Compensation}\label{approach-2-pd-gravity-compensation}}

\textbackslash{[} \textbackslash tau = K\_P\textbackslash,e + K\_D\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} + G(q) \textbackslash{]}

Adding the gravity term \textbackslash(G(q)\textbackslash) eliminates the steady-state droop at the desired position. However, during fast motions the Coriolis and inertia coupling terms still cause significant tracking errors.

\hypertarget{approach-3-computed-torque-control-inverse-dynamics}{%
\subsubsection{2.3 Approach 3: Computed Torque Control (Inverse Dynamics)}\label{approach-3-computed-torque-control-inverse-dynamics}}

The computed torque controller uses the full dynamic model to \textbf{cancel all nonlinear dynamics} and then imposes a desired linear closed-loop behaviour.

\textbf{Computed Torque Control Law}\\
\strut \\
\textbackslash{[} \textbackslash tau = M(q)\textbackslash,\textbackslash bigl{[}\textbackslash ddot\{q\}\_d + K\_D\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} + K\_P\textbackslash,e\textbackslash bigr{]} + C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\} + G(q) \textbackslash{]}

\hypertarget{derivation-step-by-step}{%
\paragraph{📐 Derivation --- Step by Step}\label{derivation-step-by-step}}

\textbf{Step 1:} Start from the robot dynamics:

\textbackslash{[} M(q)\textbackslash,\textbackslash ddot\{q\} + C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\} + G(q) = \textbackslash tau \textbackslash{]}

\textbf{Step 2:} Substitute the control law into the dynamics:

\textbackslash{[} M(q)\textbackslash,\textbackslash ddot\{q\} + \textbackslash cancel\{C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\}\} + \textbackslash cancel\{G(q)\} = M(q)\textbackslash bigl{[}\textbackslash ddot\{q\}\_d + K\_D\textbackslash dot\{e\} + K\_P e\textbackslash bigr{]} + \textbackslash cancel\{C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\}\} + \textbackslash cancel\{G(q)\} \textbackslash{]}

\textbf{Step 3:} Since \textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash) is invertible, left-multiply both sides by \textbackslash(M\^{}\{-1\}(q)\textbackslash):

\textbackslash{[} \textbackslash ddot\{q\} = \textbackslash ddot\{q\}\_d + K\_D\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} + K\_P\textbackslash,e \textbackslash{]}

\textbf{Step 4:} Since \textbackslash(\textbackslash ddot\{e\} = \textbackslash ddot\{q\}\_d - \textbackslash ddot\{q\}\textbackslash), rearrange to get the \textbf{closed-loop error dynamics}:

\textbackslash{[} \textbackslash ddot\{e\} + K\_D\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} + K\_P\textbackslash,e = 0 \textbackslash{]}

This is a \textbf{linear, decoupled, second-order ODE} for each joint --- identical to a mass--spring--damper system. With proper gain selection the error converges to zero exponentially!

\hypertarget{gain-selection-placing-closed-loop-poles}{%
\subsubsection{2.4 Gain Selection: Placing Closed-Loop Poles}\label{gain-selection-placing-closed-loop-poles}}

For each joint, the characteristic equation is \textbackslash(s\^{}2 + k\_d\textbackslash,s + k\_p = 0\textbackslash). Comparing with the standard second-order form \textbackslash(s\^{}2 + 2\textbackslash zeta\textbackslash omega\_n s + \textbackslash omega\_n\^{}2 = 0\textbackslash):

\textbackslash{[} k\_p = \textbackslash omega\_n\^{}2, \textbackslash qquad k\_d = 2\textbackslash zeta\textbackslash omega\_n \textbackslash{]}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}llllll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Design Choice & \textbackslash(\textbackslash zeta\textbackslash) & \textbackslash(\textbackslash omega\_n\textbackslash) & \textbackslash(K\_P\textbackslash) & \textbackslash(K\_D\textbackslash) & Behaviour \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
Underdamped & 0.5 & 10 & 100 & 10 & Fast but oscillatory \\
Critically damped & 1.0 & 10 & 100 & 20 & Fastest without overshoot ✓ \\
Overdamped & 2.0 & 10 & 100 & 40 & Sluggish but smooth \\
\end{longtable}

\hypertarget{lyapunov-stability-proof}{%
\subsubsection{2.5 Lyapunov Stability Proof}\label{lyapunov-stability-proof}}

Even though the computed torque controller linearises the system, we can also prove stability directly using Lyapunov theory --- which is more rigorous and generalises to uncertain models.

\hypertarget{lyapunov-proof-for-computed-torque-control}{%
\paragraph{🔒 Lyapunov Proof for Computed Torque Control}\label{lyapunov-proof-for-computed-torque-control}}

\textbf{Step 1 --- Choose a Lyapunov candidate:}

\textbackslash{[} V(e, \textbackslash dot\{e\}) = \textbackslash frac\{1\}\{2\}\textbackslash dot\{e\}\^{}T M(q)\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} + \textbackslash frac\{1\}\{2\}e\^{}T K\_P\textbackslash,e \textbackslash{]}

Since \textbackslash(M(q) \textbackslash succ 0\textbackslash) and \textbackslash(K\_P \textbackslash succ 0\textbackslash), we have \textbackslash(V \textgreater{} 0\textbackslash) for all \textbackslash((e, \textbackslash dot\{e\}) \textbackslash ne (0,0)\textbackslash).

\textbf{Step 2 --- Differentiate:}

\textbackslash{[} \textbackslash dot\{V\} = \textbackslash dot\{e\}\^{}T M(q)\textbackslash,\textbackslash ddot\{e\} + \textbackslash frac\{1\}\{2\}\textbackslash dot\{e\}\^{}T \textbackslash dot\{M\}(q)\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} + e\^{}T K\_P\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} \textbackslash{]}

\textbf{Step 3 --- Substitute the closed-loop dynamics} \textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash ddot\{e\} = -C(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash dot\{e\} - K\_D\textbackslash dot\{e\} - K\_P e\textbackslash):

\textbackslash{[} \textbackslash dot\{V\} = \textbackslash dot\{e\}\^{}T\textbackslash bigl{[}-C\textbackslash dot\{e\} - K\_D\textbackslash dot\{e\} - K\_P e\textbackslash bigr{]} + \textbackslash frac\{1\}\{2\}\textbackslash dot\{e\}\^{}T\textbackslash dot\{M\}\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} + e\^{}T K\_P\textbackslash dot\{e\} \textbackslash{]}

\textbf{Step 4 --- Apply the skew-symmetry property} \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{e\}\^{}T{[}\textbackslash dot\{M\} - 2C{]}\textbackslash dot\{e\} = 0\textbackslash):

\textbackslash{[} \textbackslash dot\{V\} = -\textbackslash dot\{e\}\^{}T K\_D\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} \textbackslash;\textbackslash leq\textbackslash; 0 \textbackslash{]}

\textbf{Step 5 --- Invoke LaSalle\textquotesingle s invariance principle:} \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{V\} = 0 \textbackslash implies \textbackslash dot\{e\} = 0 \textbackslash implies \textbackslash ddot\{e\} = 0 \textbackslash implies K\_P e = 0 \textbackslash implies e = 0\textbackslash). Therefore the equilibrium \textbackslash((e, \textbackslash dot\{e\}) = (0, 0)\textbackslash) is \textbf{asymptotically stable}. ∎

\textbf{Key Insight:} The skew-symmetry of \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{M\} - 2C\textbackslash) is what makes the cross terms cancel in the Lyapunov derivative. This is the most important structural property in robot control!

\hypertarget{quick-check-2-min}{%
\paragraph{Quick Check (2 min)}\label{quick-check-2-min}}

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  What happens if \textbackslash(K\_P = 0\textbackslash) in the Lyapunov function? Can we still guarantee that \textbackslash(e \textbackslash to 0\textbackslash)?
\item
  In the computed torque law, which term handles gravity? Which handles Coriolis coupling?
\item
  If \textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash) were identity (unit mass everywhere), how would the computed torque law simplify?
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{part-3-matlab-implementation-1}{%
\subsection{💻 Part 3 --- MATLAB Implementation}\label{part-3-matlab-implementation-1}}

We will now implement the computed torque controller for a 2-DOF manipulator step by step. The robot must track a sinusoidal trajectory:
\textbackslash(q\_d(t) = \textbackslash begin\{bmatrix\} 0.5\textbackslash sin(t) \textbackslash\textbackslash{} 0.5\textbackslash cos(t) \textbackslash end\{bmatrix\}\textbackslash).

\hypertarget{system-parameters}{%
\subsubsection{3.1 System Parameters}\label{system-parameters}}

\% ===== System Parameters =====
clear all; close all; clc;
params.m1 = 1; \% Mass of link 1 (kg)
params.m2 = 1; \% Mass of link 2 (kg)
params.l1 = 1; \% Length of link 1 (m)
params.l2 = 1; \% Length of link 2 (m)
params.g = 9.81; \% Gravitational acceleration (m/s\^{}2)
\% Control gains (critically damped, wn = 7.07)
params.Kp = diag({[}50 50{]}); \% Kp = wn\^{}2
params.Kd = diag({[}20 20{]}); \% Kd = 2*zeta*wn (zeta ≈ 1.4)
\% Simulation setup
t\_span = 0:0.01:20; \% 20 seconds, 10 ms step
q0 = {[}0; 0{]}; \% Initial joint angles
dq0 = {[}0; 0{]}; \% Initial joint velocities
x0 = {[}q0; dq0{]}; \% State vector {[}q1; q2; dq1; dq2{]}

\hypertarget{desired-trajectory-functions}{%
\subsubsection{3.2 Desired Trajectory Functions}\label{desired-trajectory-functions}}

\% ===== Desired Trajectory =====
qd = @(t) {[}0.5*sin(t); 0.5*cos(t){]};
dqd = @(t) {[}0.5*cos(t); -0.5*sin(t){]};
ddqd = @(t) {[}-0.5*sin(t); -0.5*cos(t){]};

\hypertarget{dynamics-with-computed-torque-controller}{%
\subsubsection{3.3 Dynamics with Computed Torque Controller}\label{dynamics-with-computed-torque-controller}}

\hypertarget{pseudocode}{%
\paragraph{🧮 Pseudocode}\label{pseudocode}}

📋 PSEUDOCODE --- Computed Torque Controller

FUNCTION manipulator\_dynamics(t, state, params):
EXTRACT q = state{[}1:2{]}, dq = state{[}3:4{]}
COMPUTE desired trajectory: qd(t), dqd(t), ddqd(t)
COMPUTE tracking error: e = qd - q
COMPUTE velocity error: de = dqd - dq
BUILD M(q): 2×2 mass matrix using m1, m2, l1, l2, cos(q2)
BUILD C(q,dq): 2×2 Coriolis matrix using m2, l1, l2, sin(q2), dq
BUILD G(q): 2×1 gravity vector using g, m1, m2, l1, l2
COMPUTE feedforward: a\_cmd = ddqd + Kd*de + Kp*e
COMPUTE torque: tau = M * a\_cmd + C * dq + G
COMPUTE acceleration: ddq = M \textbackslash{} (tau - C*dq - G)
RETURN {[}dq; ddq{]}

\hypertarget{matlab-code}{%
\paragraph{⚙️ MATLAB Code}\label{matlab-code}}

function dx = manipulator\_dynamics(t, x, params, qd, dqd, ddqd)
q = x(1:2); \% Joint angles
dq = x(3:4); \% Joint velocities
\% Desired trajectory at current time
q\_des = qd(t);
dq\_des = dqd(t);
ddq\_des = ddqd(t);
\% Tracking errors
e = q\_des - q;
de = dq\_des - dq;
\% -\/-\/- Build the Dynamic Model -\/-\/-
m1 = params.m1; m2 = params.m2;
l1 = params.l1; l2 = params.l2;
g = params.g;
\% Mass matrix M(q)
M11 = m1*l1\^{}2 + m2*(l1\^{}2 + l2\^{}2 + 2*l1*l2*cos(q(2)));
M12 = m2*(l2\^{}2 + l1*l2*cos(q(2)));
M22 = m2*l2\^{}2;
M = {[}M11, M12; M12, M22{]};
\% Coriolis matrix C(q, dq)
h = m2*l1*l2*sin(q(2));
C = {[}-h*dq(2), -h*(dq(1)+dq(2));
h*dq(1), 0 {]};
\% Gravity vector G(q)
G = {[}(m1+m2)*g*l1*cos(q(1)) + m2*g*l2*cos(q(1)+q(2));
m2*g*l2*cos(q(1)+q(2)) {]};
\% -\/-\/- Computed Torque Control Law -\/-\/-
a\_cmd = ddq\_des + params.Kd*de + params.Kp*e;
tau = M * a\_cmd + C * dq + G;
\% -\/-\/- Forward Dynamics -\/-\/-
ddq = M \textbackslash{} (tau - C*dq - G);
dx = {[}dq; ddq{]};
end

\textbf{Why \texttt{M\textbackslash{}b} instead of \texttt{inv(M)*b}?} The backslash operator is numerically more stable and faster. Never invert the mass matrix explicitly in production code.

\hypertarget{run-simulation-plot}{%
\subsubsection{3.4 Run Simulation \& Plot}\label{run-simulation-plot}}

\% ===== Run ODE45 =====
{[}t, x{]} = ode45(@(t,x) manipulator\_dynamics(t, x, params, qd, dqd, ddqd), ...
t\_span, x0);
\% ===== Compute desired trajectory for plotting =====
qd\_vals = zeros(length(t), 2);
for i = 1:length(t)
qd\_vals(i,:) = qd(t(i))\textquotesingle;
end
\% ===== Plot: Joint Angles =====
figure(\textquotesingle Position\textquotesingle, {[}100 100 1200 500{]});
subplot(1,2,1);
plot(t, x(:,1), \textquotesingle b\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle LineWidth\textquotesingle, 1.5); hold on;
plot(t, x(:,2), \textquotesingle r\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle LineWidth\textquotesingle, 1.5);
plot(t, qd\_vals(:,1), \textquotesingle b-\/-\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle LineWidth\textquotesingle, 1.2);
plot(t, qd\_vals(:,2), \textquotesingle r-\/-\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle LineWidth\textquotesingle, 1.2);
xlabel(\textquotesingle Time (s)\textquotesingle); ylabel(\textquotesingle Angle (rad)\textquotesingle);
title(\textquotesingle Joint Angles: Actual vs Desired\textquotesingle);
legend(\textquotesingle q\_1\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle q\_2\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle q\_\{1,d\}\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle q\_\{2,d\}\textquotesingle);
grid on;
\% ===== Plot: Tracking Error =====
subplot(1,2,2);
e\_vals = qd\_vals - x(:,1:2);
plot(t, e\_vals(:,1), \textquotesingle b\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle LineWidth\textquotesingle, 1.5); hold on;
plot(t, e\_vals(:,2), \textquotesingle r\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle LineWidth\textquotesingle, 1.5);
xlabel(\textquotesingle Time (s)\textquotesingle); ylabel(\textquotesingle Error (rad)\textquotesingle);
title(\textquotesingle Tracking Error\textquotesingle);
legend(\textquotesingle e\_1\textquotesingle, \textquotesingle e\_2\textquotesingle);
grid on;
sgtitle(\textquotesingle Computed Torque Control --- 2-DOF Manipulator\textquotesingle);

\textbf{Expected Result:} After a brief transient (≈ 1--2 s), both joint errors should converge to near zero and the actual trajectory should overlay the desired trajectory almost perfectly.

\hypertarget{hands-on-activity-1-10-min}{%
\paragraph{Hands-On Activity 1 (10 min)}\label{hands-on-activity-1-10-min}}

\textbf{Task:} Run the code above in MATLAB. Then modify the gains as follows and observe the effect on the tracking error plot:

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  Set \textbackslash(K\_P = \textbackslash text\{diag\}({[}10, 10{]})\textbackslash) and \textbackslash(K\_D = \textbackslash text\{diag\}({[}5, 5{]})\textbackslash) --- \emph{what happens?}
\item
  Set \textbackslash(K\_P = \textbackslash text\{diag\}({[}200, 200{]})\textbackslash) and \textbackslash(K\_D = \textbackslash text\{diag\}({[}5, 5{]})\textbackslash) --- \emph{is there overshoot?}
\item
  Set \textbackslash(K\_P = \textbackslash text\{diag\}({[}50, 50{]})\textbackslash) and \textbackslash(K\_D = \textbackslash text\{diag\}({[}50, 50{]})\textbackslash) --- \emph{is the response sluggish?}
\end{enumerate}

Record the peak error for each case. We will compare results as a class.

\hypertarget{comparing-control-strategies}{%
\subsection{📊 Comparing Control Strategies}\label{comparing-control-strategies}}

To appreciate why computed torque is superior, let us compare three controllers on the same trajectory.

\hypertarget{controller-a-pd-only}{%
\subsubsection{Controller A: PD Only}\label{controller-a-pd-only}}

\% Inside dynamics function, replace control law with:
tau = params.Kp * e + params.Kd * de;
\% No model terms --- ignores M, C, G completely

\hypertarget{controller-b-pd-gravity-compensation}{%
\subsubsection{Controller B: PD + Gravity Compensation}\label{controller-b-pd-gravity-compensation}}

\% Inside dynamics function, replace control law with:
tau = params.Kp * e + params.Kd * de + G;
\% Compensates gravity but ignores Coriolis and inertia coupling

\hypertarget{controller-c-computed-torque-full}{%
\subsubsection{Controller C: Computed Torque (Full)}\label{controller-c-computed-torque-full}}

\% Full computed torque (already implemented above):
a\_cmd = ddq\_des + params.Kd * de + params.Kp * e;
tau = M * a\_cmd + C * dq + G;

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lllll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Controller & Model Knowledge & Steady-State Error & Transient Error & Coupling Rejection \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
PD Only & None & Non-zero (gravity droop) & Large & Poor \\
PD + Gravity & \textbackslash(G(q)\textbackslash) & Zero at setpoints & Moderate & Moderate \\
Computed Torque & \textbackslash(M, C, G\textbackslash) & Zero & Small (tunable) & Excellent ✓ \\
\end{longtable}

\hypertarget{hands-on-activity-2-15-min}{%
\paragraph{Hands-On Activity 2 (15 min)}\label{hands-on-activity-2-15-min}}

\textbf{Task:} Implement all three controllers. Plot their tracking errors on the same figure using \texttt{subplot} or overlaid with different colours. Answer:

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  Which controller has the largest peak error during the first 2 seconds?
\item
  Which controller has a non-zero steady-state error? Why?
\item
  At what joint velocity does the PD controller start to diverge noticeably from computed torque?
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{part-4-robustness-analysis}{%
\subsection{🛡️ Part 4 --- Robustness Analysis}\label{part-4-robustness-analysis}}

Computed torque control delivers \textbf{perfect} tracking when the model is exact. In practice, we never know the model perfectly. Robustness analysis studies what happens when the model used in the controller differs from the true plant.

\hypertarget{sources-of-model-uncertainty}{%
\subsubsection{4.1 Sources of Model Uncertainty}\label{sources-of-model-uncertainty}}

\hypertarget{payload-variation}{%
\paragraph{📦 Payload Variation}\label{payload-variation}}

The mass \textbackslash(m\_2\textbackslash) changes when the robot picks up or drops objects. The controller may still use the nominal value.

\hypertarget{friction}{%
\paragraph{🔩 Friction}\label{friction}}

Real joints exhibit Coulomb and viscous friction not captured in the rigid-body model.

\hypertarget{parameter-errors}{%
\paragraph{📏 Parameter Errors}\label{parameter-errors}}

Link lengths and centres of mass are measured imprecisely. Actuator dynamics are neglected.

\hypertarget{external-disturbances}{%
\paragraph{💨 External Disturbances}\label{external-disturbances}}

Contact forces, wind loads, or interaction forces when collaborating with humans.

\hypertarget{mathematical-framework}{%
\subsubsection{4.2 Mathematical Framework}\label{mathematical-framework}}

Let the true dynamics be governed by \textbackslash((M, C, G)\textbackslash) and the \emph{estimated} (controller) model be \textbackslash((\textbackslash hat\{M\}, \textbackslash hat\{C\}, \textbackslash hat\{G\})\textbackslash). The control law uses the estimated model:

\textbackslash{[} \textbackslash tau = \textbackslash hat\{M\}(q)\textbackslash bigl{[}\textbackslash ddot\{q\}\_d + K\_D\textbackslash dot\{e\} + K\_P e\textbackslash bigr{]} + \textbackslash hat\{C\}(q,\textbackslash dot\{q\})\textbackslash dot\{q\} + \textbackslash hat\{G\}(q) \textbackslash{]}

Substituting into the true dynamics:

\textbackslash{[} M\textbackslash,\textbackslash ddot\{q\} + C\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\} + G = \textbackslash hat\{M\}\textbackslash bigl{[}\textbackslash ddot\{q\}\_d + K\_D\textbackslash dot\{e\} + K\_P e\textbackslash bigr{]} + \textbackslash hat\{C\}\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\} + \textbackslash hat\{G\} \textbackslash{]}

Defining model errors \textbackslash(\textbackslash Delta M = M - \textbackslash hat\{M\}\textbackslash), \textbackslash(\textbackslash Delta C = C - \textbackslash hat\{C\}\textbackslash), \textbackslash(\textbackslash Delta G = G - \textbackslash hat\{G\}\textbackslash), the closed-loop error dynamics become:

\textbackslash{[} M\textbackslash,\textbackslash ddot\{e\} + (C + K\_D\^{}*)\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{e\} + K\_P\^{}*\textbackslash,e = \textbackslash underbrace\{\textbackslash Delta M\textbackslash,\textbackslash ddot\{q\}\_d + \textbackslash Delta C\textbackslash,\textbackslash dot\{q\} + \textbackslash Delta G\}\_\{\textbackslash text\{perturbation \} d(t)\} \textbackslash{]}

The error no longer converges to zero --- it is driven by the perturbation \textbackslash(d(t)\textbackslash).

\textbf{Key Result:} With model mismatch, computed torque control guarantees \emph{bounded} errors (the errors stay small if the gains are high and the model errors are small), but not \emph{asymptotic} tracking to zero.

\hypertarget{experiment-payload-mismatch}{%
\subsubsection{4.3 Experiment: Payload Mismatch}\label{experiment-payload-mismatch}}

We simulate the scenario where the \textbf{true} plant has \textbackslash(m\_2 = 2\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{kg\}\textbackslash) but the controller still assumes \textbackslash(m\_2 = 1\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{kg\}\textbackslash).

\% ===== Robustness Test: Payload Mismatch =====
\% True plant parameters (what reality is)
params\_true = params;
params\_true.m2 = 2; \% True mass of link 2 is DOUBLE
\% Controller still uses params (m2 = 1) for its model
\% We need a modified dynamics function:
function dx = manipulator\_robust\_test(t, x, params\_ctrl, params\_true, qd, dqd, ddqd)
q = x(1:2);
dq = x(3:4);
q\_des = qd(t);
dq\_des = dqd(t);
ddq\_des = ddqd(t);
e = q\_des - q;
de = dq\_des - dq;
\% -\/-\/- Controller uses ESTIMATED model (params\_ctrl) -\/-\/-
{[}M\_hat, C\_hat, G\_hat{]} = build\_model(q, dq, params\_ctrl);
a\_cmd = ddq\_des + params\_ctrl.Kd*de + params\_ctrl.Kp*e;
tau = M\_hat * a\_cmd + C\_hat * dq + G\_hat;
\% -\/-\/- Plant uses TRUE model (params\_true) -\/-\/-
{[}M\_true, C\_true, G\_true{]} = build\_model(q, dq, params\_true);
ddq = M\_true \textbackslash{} (tau - C\_true*dq - G\_true);
dx = {[}dq; ddq{]};
end
function {[}M, C, G{]} = build\_model(q, dq, p)
M11 = p.m1*p.l1\^{}2 + p.m2*(p.l1\^{}2 + p.l2\^{}2 + 2*p.l1*p.l2*cos(q(2)));
M12 = p.m2*(p.l2\^{}2 + p.l1*p.l2*cos(q(2)));
M22 = p.m2*p.l2\^{}2;
M = {[}M11, M12; M12, M22{]};
h = p.m2*p.l1*p.l2*sin(q(2));
C = {[}-h*dq(2), -h*(dq(1)+dq(2)); h*dq(1), 0{]};
G = {[}(p.m1+p.m2)*p.g*p.l1*cos(q(1)) + p.m2*p.g*p.l2*cos(q(1)+q(2));
p.m2*p.g*p.l2*cos(q(1)+q(2)){]};
end

\hypertarget{experiment-adding-joint-friction}{%
\subsubsection{4.4 Experiment: Adding Joint Friction}\label{experiment-adding-joint-friction}}

\% ===== Add Coulomb + Viscous Friction =====
\% After computing ddq from the model, add friction terms:
b\_viscous = 0.5; \% Viscous friction coefficient
f\_coulomb = 0.3; \% Coulomb friction magnitude
\% Friction torque (not modelled by controller)
tau\_friction = b\_viscous * dq + f\_coulomb * sign(dq);
\% Modified acceleration (true plant sees friction)
ddq = M\_true \textbackslash{} (tau - C\_true*dq - G\_true - tau\_friction);

\hypertarget{experiment-external-disturbance-pulse}{%
\subsubsection{4.5 Experiment: External Disturbance Pulse}\label{experiment-external-disturbance-pulse}}

\% ===== External Disturbance =====
\% Simulate a sudden impact at t = 10 s lasting 0.5 s
if t \textgreater= 10 \&\& t \textless= 10.5
tau\_dist = {[}5; 3{]}; \% Disturbance torque (N·m)
else
tau\_dist = {[}0; 0{]};
end
ddq = M\_true \textbackslash{} (tau - C\_true*dq - G\_true + tau\_dist);

\hypertarget{summary-of-robustness-results}{%
\subsubsection{4.6 Summary of Robustness Results}\label{summary-of-robustness-results}}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Scenario & Peak Error (rad) & Steady-State Error & Stability \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
Perfect model & ≈ 0.02 (transient only) & ≈ 0 & Asymptotically stable \\
Payload ×2 & ≈ 0.08 -- 0.15 & Small oscillatory & Bounded (stable) \\
Joint friction & ≈ 0.03 -- 0.06 & Small bias & Bounded (stable) \\
Disturbance pulse & ≈ 0.10 (at impact) & Returns to ≈ 0 & ISS (input-to-state stable) \\
Payload ×5 + friction & ≈ 0.3 -- 0.5 & Significant & May become unstable with low gains \\
\end{longtable}

\textbf{Rule of Thumb:} Higher gains (\textbackslash(K\_P, K\_D\textbackslash)) improve robustness by rejecting perturbations faster, but they also amplify sensor noise and demand higher torques. Controller design is always a trade-off between performance, robustness, and actuator limits.

\hypertarget{hands-on-activities}{%
\subsection{🔬 Hands-On Activities}\label{hands-on-activities}}

\hypertarget{activity-3-robustness-investigation-20-min}{%
\subsubsection{Activity 3: Robustness Investigation (20 min)}\label{activity-3-robustness-investigation-20-min}}

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  Start with the nominal computed torque controller (\textbackslash(m\_2 = 1\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{kg\}\textbackslash) in both plant and controller).
\item
  Change the \textbf{true} \textbackslash(m\_2\textbackslash) to 1.5, 2.0, 3.0, and 5.0 kg while keeping the controller model at \textbackslash(m\_2 = 1\textbackslash).
\item
  For each case, record the maximum tracking error \textbackslash(\textbackslash\textbar e\textbackslash\textbar\_\textbackslash infty\textbackslash) from the error plot.
\item
  Plot \textbackslash(\textbackslash\textbar e\textbackslash\textbar\_\textbackslash infty\textbackslash) vs payload ratio \textbackslash(m\_\{2,\textbackslash text\{true\}\} / m\_\{2,\textbackslash text\{ctrl\}\}\textbackslash).
\item
  \textbf{Bonus:} At what payload ratio does the system become unstable? Increase \textbackslash(K\_P\textbackslash) and \textbackslash(K\_D\textbackslash) --- does this extend the stability boundary?
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Expected Observation:} Tracking error grows approximately linearly with payload mismatch for small mismatches, but growth accelerates for large mismatches.

\hypertarget{activity-4-controller-comparison-dashboard-25-min}{%
