Create a single MATLAB figure with a 3×2 subplot layout:

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
& Column 1: Joint Angles & Column 2: Tracking Error \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\textbf{Row 1} & PD Only --- actual vs desired & PD Only --- error \\
\textbf{Row 2} & PD + Gravity --- actual vs desired & PD + Gravity --- error \\
\textbf{Row 3} & Computed Torque --- actual vs desired & Computed Torque --- error \\
\end{longtable}

Use the same gains and trajectory for all three. Include a title, legends, and axis labels on every subplot.

\hypertarget{activity-5-design-challenge-15-min}{%
\subsubsection{Activity 5: Design Challenge (15 min)}\label{activity-5-design-challenge-15-min}}

\hypertarget{challenge-robust-trajectory-tracking}{%
\paragraph{🏆 Challenge: Robust Trajectory Tracking}\label{challenge-robust-trajectory-tracking}}

Design a controller that can track the reference trajectory with \textbackslash(\textbackslash\textbar e\textbackslash\textbar\_\textbackslash infty \textless{} 0.05\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{rad\}\textbackslash) under the following \textbf{simultaneous} conditions:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  True \textbackslash(m\_2 = 2\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{kg\}\textbackslash), controller assumes \textbackslash(m\_2 = 1\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{kg\}\textbackslash)
\item
  Viscous friction \textbackslash(b = 0.5\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{N·m·s/rad\}\textbackslash) (not modelled)
\item
  An external disturbance of \textbackslash(\textbackslash tau\_d = {[}3; 2{]}\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{N·m\}\textbackslash) applied from \textbackslash(t = 8\textbackslash) to \textbackslash(t = 8.5\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{s\}\textbackslash)
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Hint:} You may increase gains, add integral action, or add a robust term \textbackslash(\textbackslash tau\_\{\textbackslash text\{robust\}\} = K\_r\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{sign\}(\textbackslash dot\{e\})\textbackslash).

\hypertarget{end-of-lecture-quiz}{%
\subsection{🧠 End-of-Lecture Quiz}\label{end-of-lecture-quiz}}

\hypertarget{test-your-understanding}{%
\paragraph{Test Your Understanding}\label{test-your-understanding}}

\begin{enumerate}
\item
  \textbf{True or False:} The mass matrix \textbackslash(M(q)\textbackslash) is always diagonal for a 2-DOF manipulator.

  \emph{Think about what the off-diagonal terms represent physically.}
\item
  \textbf{Fill in the blank:} The property that \textbackslash(\textbackslash dot\{M\} - 2C\textbackslash) is \_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_\_ is essential for the Lyapunov stability proof of computed torque control.
\item
  \textbf{Short answer:} Name two practical reasons why computed torque control may not achieve perfect tracking on a real robot.
\item
  \textbf{Calculation:} For a desired natural frequency \textbackslash(\textbackslash omega\_n = 15\textbackslash,\textbackslash text\{rad/s\}\textbackslash) and critical damping (\textbackslash(\textbackslash zeta = 1\textbackslash)), compute \textbackslash(K\_P\textbackslash) and \textbackslash(K\_D\textbackslash) per joint.
\item
  \textbf{Design question:} If you double all link masses simultaneously, but the controller model remains unchanged, how does the perturbation term \textbackslash(d(t)\textbackslash) scale? Would increasing \textbackslash(K\_P\textbackslash) alone fix the problem? Why or why not?
\end{enumerate}

Click to reveal answers

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{False.} The off-diagonal terms \textbackslash(M\_\{12\} = M\_\{21\}\textbackslash) capture inertia coupling between joints. They are zero only in special configurations.
\item
  \textbf{Skew-symmetric.}
\item
  Any two of: model parameter uncertainty, unmodelled friction, actuator saturation/dynamics, sensor noise, discretisation effects, joint flexibility.
\item
  \textbackslash(K\_P = \textbackslash omega\_n\^{}2 = 225\textbackslash), \textbackslash(K\_D = 2 \textbackslash times 1 \textbackslash times 15 = 30\textbackslash).
\item
  The perturbation scales proportionally with the mass error \textbackslash(\textbackslash Delta M\textbackslash), which doubles. Increasing \textbackslash(K\_P\textbackslash) alone gives faster error correction but does not cancel the feedforward mismatch --- you also need higher \textbackslash(K\_D\textbackslash) to damp the resulting oscillations, or better yet, update the model.
\end{enumerate}

